WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.776 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING][RUSTLING][CLICKING]

00:00:06.776 --> 00:00:11.140 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.140 --> 00:00:12.520 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: OK.

00:00:12.520 --> 00:00:14.240 align:middle line:90%
Let us start.

00:00:14.240 --> 00:00:19.600 align:middle line:84%
So last time, we started talking
about interacting theories.

00:00:19.600 --> 00:00:24.790 align:middle line:84%
And here is the simplest
interacting theory

00:00:24.790 --> 00:00:28.600 align:middle line:84%
with the Lagrangian
density of the form.

00:00:28.600 --> 00:00:38.360 align:middle line:90%


00:00:38.360 --> 00:00:38.860 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:00:38.860 --> 00:00:41.560 align:middle line:84%
So this is just
the simplest one.

00:00:41.560 --> 00:00:44.590 align:middle line:84%
And we will use
this as our example

00:00:44.590 --> 00:00:50.080 align:middle line:84%
to illustrate how you treat
interacting theories, OK--

00:00:50.080 --> 00:00:53.770 align:middle line:84%
how you treat the particles
with interactions.

00:00:53.770 --> 00:00:56.170 align:middle line:84%
Once we understand
how to do one theory,

00:00:56.170 --> 00:01:01.820 align:middle line:84%
essentially you will know
how to do all of them.

00:01:01.820 --> 00:01:06.370 align:middle line:90%
And we also said that the--

00:01:06.370 --> 00:01:13.180 align:middle line:84%
a key quantity when talking
about interactions--

00:01:13.180 --> 00:01:14.620 align:middle line:90%
a key observable--

00:01:14.620 --> 00:01:16.960 align:middle line:90%
is called S-matrix.

00:01:16.960 --> 00:01:23.630 align:middle line:84%
So S-matrix is defined
as the following.

00:01:23.630 --> 00:01:26.650 align:middle line:90%
So S beta alpha beta--

00:01:26.650 --> 00:01:35.740 align:middle line:84%
beta alpha equal to beta U plus
infinity minus infinity alpha.

00:01:35.740 --> 00:01:39.570 align:middle line:84%
So you start with some
alpha initial state,

00:01:39.570 --> 00:01:41.360 align:middle line:84%
which are widely
separated, which

00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:45.850 align:middle line:84%
you can treat as a
collections of free particles.

00:01:45.850 --> 00:01:50.530 align:middle line:84%
And then say as T goes
to minus infinity,

00:01:50.530 --> 00:01:53.350 align:middle line:90%
they are very widely separated.

00:01:53.350 --> 00:01:56.080 align:middle line:84%
But then as time evolves,
they will come together,

00:01:56.080 --> 00:01:57.790 align:middle line:90%
the scatter.

00:01:57.790 --> 00:02:01.430 align:middle line:84%
Then they will separate
into far future.

00:02:01.430 --> 00:02:04.460 align:middle line:84%
And so that's our
final state beta.

00:02:04.460 --> 00:02:07.480 align:middle line:84%
And so S alpha beta is
the transition amplitude

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:08.440 align:middle line:90%
between the two.

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:08.940 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:02:08.940 --> 00:02:12.130 align:middle line:84%
So this is the written in terms
of the Schrodinger picture.

00:02:12.130 --> 00:02:18.350 align:middle line:84%
You can also written in terms
of the Heisenberg picture,

00:02:18.350 --> 00:02:21.110 align:middle line:84%
which is normally
written in this form.

00:02:21.110 --> 00:02:21.610 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:02:21.610 --> 00:02:26.300 align:middle line:90%


00:02:26.300 --> 00:02:27.860 align:middle line:90%
So-- and we often--

00:02:27.860 --> 00:02:30.590 align:middle line:90%


00:02:30.590 --> 00:02:34.070 align:middle line:84%
so it's often
convenient to write

00:02:34.070 --> 00:02:38.750 align:middle line:84%
this S alpha beta separated
into identity part delta

00:02:38.750 --> 00:02:43.310 align:middle line:84%
beta alpha and then
plus i T beta alpha.

00:02:43.310 --> 00:02:46.920 align:middle line:84%
So this will capture the
effect of the interactions.

00:02:46.920 --> 00:02:49.260 align:middle line:84%
We'll capture the effect
of the interactions.

00:02:49.260 --> 00:02:54.470 align:middle line:90%
And so-- and since the--

00:02:54.470 --> 00:02:57.350 align:middle line:84%
such as-- yeah,
we always consider

00:02:57.350 --> 00:03:02.670 align:middle line:84%
theories which are both spatial
and the time translation

00:03:02.670 --> 00:03:03.170 align:middle line:90%
invariant.

00:03:03.170 --> 00:03:06.440 align:middle line:84%
So you have energy
momentum conservation.

00:03:06.440 --> 00:03:10.550 align:middle line:90%
And so i T alpha--

00:03:10.550 --> 00:03:16.840 align:middle line:84%
i T beta alpha will always
contain a piece proportional--

00:03:16.840 --> 00:03:19.060 align:middle line:90%
we also put i here--

00:03:19.060 --> 00:03:25.810 align:middle line:90%
proportional to the moment--

00:03:25.810 --> 00:03:27.532 align:middle line:90%
the momentum conservation.

00:03:27.532 --> 00:03:34.420 align:middle line:90%


00:03:34.420 --> 00:03:35.080 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:35.080 --> 00:03:38.620 align:middle line:84%
So p alpha-- and the p alpha
is the total initial momentum.

00:03:38.620 --> 00:03:46.100 align:middle line:90%


00:03:46.100 --> 00:03:47.860 align:middle line:90%
So here is full momentum, OK?

00:03:47.860 --> 00:03:49.570 align:middle line:90%
So I suppress the indices.

00:03:49.570 --> 00:03:54.790 align:middle line:84%
And the p beta is the
total final momentum.

00:03:54.790 --> 00:04:00.770 align:middle line:90%


00:04:00.770 --> 00:04:03.250 align:middle line:84%
So this part is
purely kinematic.

00:04:03.250 --> 00:04:06.290 align:middle line:84%
So the M alpha beta
is the physical part.

00:04:06.290 --> 00:04:06.790 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:06.790 --> 00:04:09.640 align:middle line:84%
So this is normally called
the scattering amplitude.

00:04:09.640 --> 00:04:20.380 align:middle line:90%


00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:22.210 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:22.210 --> 00:04:25.900 align:middle line:84%
So our goal is to be able
to calculate the scattering

00:04:25.900 --> 00:04:27.290 align:middle line:90%
amplitude.

00:04:27.290 --> 00:04:27.790 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:27.790 --> 00:04:31.550 align:middle line:84%
So this is something--
some version

00:04:31.550 --> 00:04:33.050 align:middle line:84%
of the scattering
amplitude that can

00:04:33.050 --> 00:04:34.650 align:middle line:90%
be measured in the experiments.

00:04:34.650 --> 00:04:37.310 align:middle line:84%
So theoretically, we want
to be able to calculate

00:04:37.310 --> 00:04:38.700 align:middle line:90%
this quantity.

00:04:38.700 --> 00:04:42.320 align:middle line:84%
So they'll be able to
compare with the experiments.

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:45.225 align:middle line:90%
So we also mentioned--

00:04:45.225 --> 00:04:47.240 align:middle line:84%
I will not repeat
here-- we also mentioned

00:04:47.240 --> 00:04:50.330 align:middle line:84%
that this S alpha
beta, S beta alpha

00:04:50.330 --> 00:04:54.770 align:middle line:84%
also have various
properties, which

00:04:54.770 --> 00:05:02.310 align:middle line:84%
you should go back to your notes
of last class to review them.

00:05:02.310 --> 00:05:08.570 align:middle line:84%
So one of the key points
is the LSZ theorem,

00:05:08.570 --> 00:05:11.620 align:middle line:84%
which said, which
I just mentioned,

00:05:11.620 --> 00:05:24.360 align:middle line:84%
that M alpha beta can be
obtained from a correlation

00:05:24.360 --> 00:05:25.950 align:middle line:90%
function, like this.

00:05:25.950 --> 00:05:34.250 align:middle line:84%
Say, for example,
for that theory, OK?

00:05:34.250 --> 00:05:36.770 align:middle line:84%
So the n would correspond
to the total number

00:05:36.770 --> 00:05:40.070 align:middle line:84%
of particles of the
initial plus final states.

00:05:40.070 --> 00:05:42.470 align:middle line:84%
So suppose you have
2 to 2 scattering,

00:05:42.470 --> 00:05:45.260 align:middle line:90%
and then n would be equal to 4.

00:05:45.260 --> 00:05:47.720 align:middle line:84%
So if you start
from 2 particles,

00:05:47.720 --> 00:05:50.450 align:middle line:84%
you scattering to 3
particles, then n will be 5.

00:05:50.450 --> 00:05:53.240 align:middle line:90%
OK, just the total number, yeah.

00:05:53.240 --> 00:05:56.360 align:middle line:84%
So later, we will discuss,
in more detail, how you

00:05:56.360 --> 00:05:59.240 align:middle line:90%
obtain M alpha beta from here.

00:05:59.240 --> 00:06:01.850 align:middle line:84%
But here, at the moment,
it's enough for us

00:06:01.850 --> 00:06:05.300 align:middle line:84%
to know that the
scattering amplitude can be

00:06:05.300 --> 00:06:07.410 align:middle line:90%
extracted from this quantity.

00:06:07.410 --> 00:06:10.682 align:middle line:90%
Oh, sorry, I should--

00:06:10.682 --> 00:06:12.140 align:middle line:84%
So here, it should
be time ordered.

00:06:12.140 --> 00:06:19.700 align:middle line:90%


00:06:19.700 --> 00:06:23.250 align:middle line:84%
And so let me just
explain the notation here.

00:06:23.250 --> 00:06:30.500 align:middle line:84%
So the omega is the vacuum
of your interacting theory.

00:06:30.500 --> 00:06:32.870 align:middle line:90%
And then the T is time ordering.

00:06:32.870 --> 00:06:41.180 align:middle line:90%


00:06:41.180 --> 00:06:45.020 align:middle line:84%
It means that, whoever
with the larger time,

00:06:45.020 --> 00:06:48.350 align:middle line:90%
it will appear earlier.

00:06:48.350 --> 00:06:51.330 align:middle line:84%
Whoever with a larger
time will appear earlier.

00:06:51.330 --> 00:06:53.780 align:middle line:90%
And so any questions on this?

00:06:53.780 --> 00:07:00.530 align:middle line:90%


00:07:00.530 --> 00:07:04.960 align:middle line:84%
So our goal would be to tell you
how to calculate this quantity.

00:07:04.960 --> 00:07:07.010 align:middle line:84%
So once you know how to
calculate this quantity,

00:07:07.010 --> 00:07:09.010 align:middle line:84%
then we will be able to
calculate the scattering

00:07:09.010 --> 00:07:09.700 align:middle line:90%
amplitude.

00:07:09.700 --> 00:07:13.840 align:middle line:84%
And then you will be able
to compare with experiments.

00:07:13.840 --> 00:07:18.680 align:middle line:90%
And good.

00:07:18.680 --> 00:07:22.940 align:middle line:84%
So in principle, we already know
how to calculate this quantity

00:07:22.940 --> 00:07:25.550 align:middle line:90%
from what you learned in 8.06.

00:07:25.550 --> 00:07:30.170 align:middle line:84%
So for people who have taken
8.06, here, you learned.

00:07:30.170 --> 00:07:33.470 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so we mentioned last time,
this theory cannot be solved,

00:07:33.470 --> 00:07:34.340 align:middle line:90%
exactly.

00:07:34.340 --> 00:07:36.230 align:middle line:84%
And the only way we
can treat this theory

00:07:36.230 --> 00:07:42.140 align:middle line:84%
is to take lambda small and then
treat this as a perturbation,

00:07:42.140 --> 00:07:43.910 align:middle line:84%
treat this as a
small perturbation,

00:07:43.910 --> 00:07:46.640 align:middle line:84%
and then expand all
your physical quantities

00:07:46.640 --> 00:07:48.080 align:middle line:90%
in power series of lambda.

00:07:48.080 --> 00:07:50.940 align:middle line:90%


00:07:50.940 --> 00:07:53.780 align:middle line:84%
So this procedure is
called perturbation theory.

00:07:53.780 --> 00:07:58.190 align:middle line:84%
And in your quantum
mechanics class,

00:07:58.190 --> 00:08:03.140 align:middle line:84%
you should have already learned
how to do perturbation theory.

00:08:03.140 --> 00:08:07.790 align:middle line:84%
For example, in 8.06, that's
a big part of the 8.06 class.

00:08:07.790 --> 00:08:12.440 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, so just with 8.06,
in principle, you already

00:08:12.440 --> 00:08:13.410 align:middle line:90%
know how to do this.

00:08:13.410 --> 00:08:15.086 align:middle line:84%
Let me just outline
the procedure--

00:08:15.086 --> 00:08:22.350 align:middle line:90%


00:08:22.350 --> 00:08:23.440 align:middle line:90%
a computation.

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:28.980 align:middle line:90%


00:08:28.980 --> 00:08:31.470 align:middle line:84%
So that is a
correlation function.

00:08:31.470 --> 00:08:35.045 align:middle line:84%
So it's called a time
ordered correlation function.

00:08:35.045 --> 00:08:51.190 align:middle line:90%


00:08:51.190 --> 00:08:55.880 align:middle line:84%
So what I will call this is
a naive perturbation theory.

00:08:55.880 --> 00:08:58.380 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
perturbation theory

00:08:58.380 --> 00:09:03.530 align:middle line:84%
you would do after
you learned 8.06, OK,

00:09:03.530 --> 00:09:05.147 align:middle line:84%
after you learned
8.06, and then you

00:09:05.147 --> 00:09:06.980 align:middle line:84%
will be able to do this
perturbation theory.

00:09:06.980 --> 00:09:12.350 align:middle line:90%


00:09:12.350 --> 00:09:16.640 align:middle line:84%
But we will do something
more clever, OK?

00:09:16.640 --> 00:09:19.460 align:middle line:84%
We will do something
more clever.

00:09:19.460 --> 00:09:22.610 align:middle line:84%
But let me just
remind you, equipped

00:09:22.610 --> 00:09:24.980 align:middle line:84%
with your previous quantum
mechanical knowledge,

00:09:24.980 --> 00:09:27.890 align:middle line:84%
how would you
treat this problem?

00:09:27.890 --> 00:09:34.030 align:middle line:84%
So now let's consider, again,
that theory as example.

00:09:34.030 --> 00:09:38.410 align:middle line:84%
So the equation of
motion gives you

00:09:38.410 --> 00:09:44.290 align:middle line:84%
partial square, minus m square
phi equal to, say, lambda

00:09:44.290 --> 00:09:45.580 align:middle line:90%
divided by 6 phi cubed.

00:09:45.580 --> 00:09:48.690 align:middle line:90%


00:09:48.690 --> 00:09:57.060 align:middle line:84%
And so we can solve this
equation even though we cannot

00:09:57.060 --> 00:09:59.430 align:middle line:90%
solve this equation exactly.

00:09:59.430 --> 00:10:01.620 align:middle line:84%
We can solve it for
perturbatively in lambda.

00:10:01.620 --> 00:10:09.960 align:middle line:90%


00:10:09.960 --> 00:10:12.370 align:middle line:84%
So the way we do it
is the following.

00:10:12.370 --> 00:10:19.230 align:middle line:84%
We write phi equal to phi 0,
and the lambda phi 1 plus lambda

00:10:19.230 --> 00:10:22.260 align:middle line:90%
squared phi 2, et cetera.

00:10:22.260 --> 00:10:24.030 align:middle line:90%
So lambda is a small number.

00:10:24.030 --> 00:10:29.460 align:middle line:84%
You imagine you expand phi
in power series of lambda.

00:10:29.460 --> 00:10:31.680 align:middle line:84%
And then you just plug
in this power series

00:10:31.680 --> 00:10:36.210 align:middle line:84%
into this equation, and
then you equate two side

00:10:36.210 --> 00:10:38.640 align:middle line:90%
with the same power of lambda.

00:10:38.640 --> 00:10:39.930 align:middle line:90%
With the same power of lambda?

00:10:39.930 --> 00:10:46.410 align:middle line:84%
So the 0th order, you just
get our previous equation,

00:10:46.410 --> 00:10:47.790 align:middle line:90%
phi 0 equal to 0.

00:10:47.790 --> 00:10:52.030 align:middle line:84%
So phi 0 is just like our
previous free field equation.

00:10:52.030 --> 00:10:55.360 align:middle line:90%


00:10:55.360 --> 00:11:01.750 align:middle line:84%
And then at 1st order,
then you see phi 1,

00:11:01.750 --> 00:11:07.540 align:middle line:84%
and now you have 1 over 6
phi 0 to the cube, and then

00:11:07.540 --> 00:11:08.050 align:middle line:90%
et cetera.

00:11:08.050 --> 00:11:11.880 align:middle line:90%


00:11:11.880 --> 00:11:14.850 align:middle line:84%
So this equation, we
know how to solve.

00:11:14.850 --> 00:11:18.130 align:middle line:84%
And once you know how
to solve this equation,

00:11:18.130 --> 00:11:20.070 align:middle line:84%
you find a solution
for phi 0, then

00:11:20.070 --> 00:11:21.810 align:middle line:90%
you plug it in this equation.

00:11:21.810 --> 00:11:23.820 align:middle line:84%
And now this just becomes
a linear equation.

00:11:23.820 --> 00:11:25.290 align:middle line:90%
Now you can solve phi 1.

00:11:25.290 --> 00:11:27.870 align:middle line:84%
And similarly, you can
solve phi 2, et cetera.

00:11:27.870 --> 00:11:30.270 align:middle line:84%
So order by order, you
can solve all of them.

00:11:30.270 --> 00:11:33.780 align:middle line:84%
And all of them become
linear equations.

00:11:33.780 --> 00:11:40.230 align:middle line:90%


00:11:40.230 --> 00:11:50.670 align:middle line:84%
So phi 1 -- all higher orders
can be solved in terms of phi

00:11:50.670 --> 00:11:51.750 align:middle line:90%
0.

00:11:51.750 --> 00:11:56.640 align:middle line:84%
So once you find the
phi 0, and then phi 0

00:11:56.640 --> 00:11:58.200 align:middle line:90%
can be solved in terms of phi 0.

00:11:58.200 --> 00:12:05.650 align:middle line:90%


00:12:05.650 --> 00:12:09.290 align:middle line:84%
So classically, this
gives you a solution.

00:12:09.290 --> 00:12:12.550 align:middle line:84%
And as we said, quantum
mechanically, we just

00:12:12.550 --> 00:12:16.630 align:middle line:84%
treat this, treat all of
this as operator equations.

00:12:16.630 --> 00:12:20.350 align:middle line:84%
And then, essentially,
you can just

00:12:20.350 --> 00:12:24.130 align:middle line:84%
solve the phi, perturbatively,
as the operator equation--

00:12:24.130 --> 00:12:26.140 align:middle line:90%
as a quantum operator.

00:12:26.140 --> 00:12:29.800 align:middle line:84%
And then you solve this
quantum operator equation,

00:12:29.800 --> 00:12:31.090 align:middle line:90%
perturbatively.

00:12:31.090 --> 00:12:45.840 align:middle line:90%


00:12:45.840 --> 00:12:58.270 align:middle line:84%
So similarly, we
can solve this omega

00:12:58.270 --> 00:13:00.410 align:middle line:90%
using perturbation theory.

00:13:00.410 --> 00:13:02.050 align:middle line:90%
So first, we expand again.

00:13:02.050 --> 00:13:05.600 align:middle line:90%
We expand this omega in power.

00:13:05.600 --> 00:13:08.170 align:middle line:84%
So this is the vacuum of
the interacting theory.

00:13:08.170 --> 00:13:12.685 align:middle line:84%
And we expand it into
a perturbative series.

00:13:12.685 --> 00:13:26.230 align:middle line:90%


00:13:26.230 --> 00:13:31.610 align:middle line:84%
So the 0th order, you just
get the free theory vacuum.

00:13:31.610 --> 00:13:35.600 align:middle line:84%
And then you will have
corrections from the lambda,

00:13:35.600 --> 00:13:38.780 align:middle line:84%
here, due to you
have interactions

00:13:38.780 --> 00:13:41.360 align:middle line:84%
and because your
Hamiltonian change.

00:13:41.360 --> 00:13:43.620 align:middle line:84%
Because of the lambda,
your Hamiltonian change.

00:13:43.620 --> 00:13:45.990 align:middle line:84%
And so your ground
state will also change.

00:13:45.990 --> 00:13:49.340 align:middle line:84%
And so, now, you
can use your 8.06

00:13:49.340 --> 00:13:54.680 align:middle line:84%
to work out those higher
order corrections.

00:13:54.680 --> 00:14:01.150 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so now when you
worked out the phi,

00:14:01.150 --> 00:14:03.940 align:middle line:84%
when you worked
out the omega, now,

00:14:03.940 --> 00:14:06.140 align:middle line:90%
you can work out this object.

00:14:06.140 --> 00:14:09.580 align:middle line:90%
So let me just call this G n.

00:14:09.580 --> 00:14:23.000 align:middle line:84%
So the G n then can be reduced
to a calculation free theory.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:33.060 align:middle line:90%


00:14:33.060 --> 00:14:35.190 align:middle line:84%
And you need
perturbation theory,

00:14:35.190 --> 00:14:38.340 align:middle line:84%
because everything can be
expressed in terms of phi 0.

00:14:38.340 --> 00:14:41.250 align:middle line:84%
And here, again, you
expand in terms of phi 0.

00:14:41.250 --> 00:14:45.780 align:middle line:84%
And the corrections can
be obtained by, say, phi 0

00:14:45.780 --> 00:14:48.550 align:middle line:84%
acting on a vacuum
state, et cetera.

00:14:48.550 --> 00:14:51.240 align:middle line:84%
So in the end, if you
do this procedure,

00:14:51.240 --> 00:14:55.080 align:middle line:84%
then you should be able
to calculate this G n.

00:14:55.080 --> 00:14:57.750 align:middle line:84%
Conceptually, it's not very
difficult to calculate.

00:14:57.750 --> 00:15:01.450 align:middle line:90%


00:15:01.450 --> 00:15:03.850 align:middle line:84%
But this procedure is
actually very complicated.

00:15:03.850 --> 00:15:08.590 align:middle line:90%


00:15:08.590 --> 00:15:10.730 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, I don't urge you
to try it yourself.

00:15:10.730 --> 00:15:13.270 align:middle line:84%
But I think you
should try just to get

00:15:13.270 --> 00:15:18.665 align:middle line:84%
the sense that this procedure
is actually not very easy to do.

00:15:18.665 --> 00:15:20.290 align:middle line:84%
So that's why, in
quantum field theory,

00:15:20.290 --> 00:15:24.370 align:middle line:84%
we actually need to develop a
more sophisticated technique

00:15:24.370 --> 00:15:25.810 align:middle line:90%
to treat this.

00:15:25.810 --> 00:15:29.770 align:middle line:84%
Because that's what people
did in the early days.

00:15:29.770 --> 00:15:34.268 align:middle line:84%
In the early days, before
systematic perturbation

00:15:34.268 --> 00:15:36.310 align:middle line:84%
technique for quantum
field theory was developed,

00:15:36.310 --> 00:15:38.470 align:middle line:84%
that's how people
did it in the past.

00:15:38.470 --> 00:15:41.590 align:middle line:90%


00:15:41.590 --> 00:15:42.790 align:middle line:90%
And that was not easy.

00:15:42.790 --> 00:15:45.070 align:middle line:90%
But people did it.

00:15:45.070 --> 00:15:47.650 align:middle line:90%


00:15:47.650 --> 00:15:49.600 align:middle line:84%
So if you want to
calculate, the 1st order,

00:15:49.600 --> 00:15:50.590 align:middle line:90%
it's actually doable.

00:15:50.590 --> 00:15:55.600 align:middle line:84%
But the higher orders become
increasingly complicated.

00:15:55.600 --> 00:16:04.312 align:middle line:84%
And quickly becomes
very complicated

00:16:04.312 --> 00:16:05.520 align:middle line:90%
when you go to higher orders.

00:16:05.520 --> 00:16:21.910 align:middle line:90%


00:16:21.910 --> 00:16:27.610 align:middle line:84%
So eventually, people developed
something more clever.

00:16:27.610 --> 00:16:32.040 align:middle line:84%
So eventually, people developed
something more clever.

00:16:32.040 --> 00:16:35.240 align:middle line:90%
So there are two approaches.

00:16:35.240 --> 00:16:40.730 align:middle line:84%
There are two more
sophisticated approaches, which

00:16:40.730 --> 00:16:44.490 align:middle line:90%
are, in the end, equivalent.

00:16:44.490 --> 00:16:48.320 align:middle line:84%
OK, in the end,
they're equivalent,

00:16:48.320 --> 00:16:51.680 align:middle line:84%
but their derivation
is different.

00:16:51.680 --> 00:16:55.940 align:middle line:84%
So the first is you use
so-called interaction picture.

00:16:55.940 --> 00:17:05.430 align:middle line:90%


00:17:05.430 --> 00:17:08.359 align:middle line:84%
You use so-called
interaction picture.

00:17:08.359 --> 00:17:10.682 align:middle line:84%
So what do you do
is the following.

00:17:10.682 --> 00:17:12.849 align:middle line:84%
So you separate your
Hamiltonian, total Hamiltonian,

00:17:12.849 --> 00:17:15.970 align:middle line:84%
in terms of a free theory
Hamiltonian and the interacting

00:17:15.970 --> 00:17:17.752 align:middle line:90%
part.

00:17:17.752 --> 00:17:19.210 align:middle line:84%
So the free theory
Hamiltonian just

00:17:19.210 --> 00:17:30.500 align:middle line:84%
comes from, say, if I write
this as L0 minus that plus L I--

00:17:30.500 --> 00:17:36.220 align:middle line:84%
so this term is L I,
so this part is L0.

00:17:36.220 --> 00:17:40.840 align:middle line:84%
And so similarly, you can
write your Hamiltonian-- also

00:17:40.840 --> 00:17:44.140 align:middle line:84%
separate into the free theory
Hamiltonian and the interacting

00:17:44.140 --> 00:17:45.910 align:middle line:90%
part.

00:17:45.910 --> 00:17:49.630 align:middle line:84%
And then the
interacting picture--

00:17:49.630 --> 00:17:53.440 align:middle line:84%
it introduces the state
into interacting picture,

00:17:53.440 --> 00:17:58.090 align:middle line:84%
and you introduce the operator
in the interacting picture.

00:17:58.090 --> 00:18:00.760 align:middle line:84%
So the state, in the
interacting picture,

00:18:00.760 --> 00:18:09.290 align:middle line:84%
are related by the standard
state in the Schrodinger

00:18:09.290 --> 00:18:09.790 align:middle line:90%
picture.

00:18:09.790 --> 00:18:18.960 align:middle line:90%


00:18:18.960 --> 00:18:21.420 align:middle line:90%
So let me just put S here.

00:18:21.420 --> 00:18:24.150 align:middle line:84%
So this denotes the states
in the Schrodinger picture,

00:18:24.150 --> 00:18:26.400 align:middle line:90%
through this factor of H0--

00:18:26.400 --> 00:18:29.550 align:middle line:90%
basically, i H0 t.

00:18:29.550 --> 00:18:34.050 align:middle line:84%
And the operators in
the interacting picture

00:18:34.050 --> 00:18:41.490 align:middle line:84%
are related to the operator
in the Schrodinger picture,

00:18:41.490 --> 00:18:43.980 align:middle line:84%
also, through this factor
of the exponential of H0.

00:18:43.980 --> 00:18:51.323 align:middle line:90%


00:18:51.323 --> 00:18:52.740 align:middle line:84%
Already in your
quantum mechanics,

00:18:52.740 --> 00:18:54.990 align:middle line:84%
you may have discussed
the interaction picture.

00:18:54.990 --> 00:18:57.120 align:middle line:84%
Have you seen the
interaction picture before?

00:18:57.120 --> 00:18:57.720 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:18:57.720 --> 00:19:00.480 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:19:00.480 --> 00:19:04.200 align:middle line:84%
So remember this evolves
with the full Hamiltonian.

00:19:04.200 --> 00:19:06.600 align:middle line:84%
In the Schrodinger
picture, this evolves

00:19:06.600 --> 00:19:08.460 align:middle line:90%
with the full Hamiltonian.

00:19:08.460 --> 00:19:13.350 align:middle line:84%
And so, here, the
interaction picture

00:19:13.350 --> 00:19:16.680 align:middle line:84%
related this by evolution
operator-- conjugate

00:19:16.680 --> 00:19:20.040 align:middle line:84%
of the evolution operator
for the free Hamiltonian.

00:19:20.040 --> 00:19:23.790 align:middle line:84%
So this Psi I is still
evolved in a complicated way.

00:19:23.790 --> 00:19:26.070 align:middle line:84%
So in the interacting
picture, the states still

00:19:26.070 --> 00:19:27.810 align:middle line:90%
evolves in a complicated way.

00:19:27.810 --> 00:19:29.910 align:middle line:84%
But the operator
evolve very simply,

00:19:29.910 --> 00:19:32.790 align:middle line:84%
because, in the
Schrodinger picture,

00:19:32.790 --> 00:19:34.530 align:middle line:90%
the operator don't evolve.

00:19:34.530 --> 00:19:37.020 align:middle line:84%
And here, the evolution
just controlled

00:19:37.020 --> 00:19:39.900 align:middle line:90%
by the free Hamiltonian.

00:19:39.900 --> 00:19:42.210 align:middle line:84%
So in the interacting
picture, the states

00:19:42.210 --> 00:19:45.750 align:middle line:84%
still evolve, complicatedly,
but the operator

00:19:45.750 --> 00:19:47.790 align:middle line:90%
evolves in a simple way.

00:19:47.790 --> 00:19:53.100 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, with some manipulation,
by introducing this interacting

00:19:53.100 --> 00:20:00.420 align:middle line:84%
picture, you can design a
more clever way to do this,

00:20:00.420 --> 00:20:03.330 align:middle line:90%
to do the perturbation theory.

00:20:03.330 --> 00:20:05.550 align:middle line:84%
And so I will not
go through it, here.

00:20:05.550 --> 00:20:15.690 align:middle line:84%
You should read the book, Peskin
and Schroeder, section 4.2.

00:20:15.690 --> 00:20:18.900 align:middle line:84%
And there they give
a detailed discussion

00:20:18.900 --> 00:20:25.530 align:middle line:84%
how you do perturbation theory
using this interacting picture.

00:20:25.530 --> 00:20:29.940 align:middle line:84%
So a second approach is
to use the path integral.

00:20:29.940 --> 00:20:37.620 align:middle line:90%


00:20:37.620 --> 00:20:39.600 align:middle line:90%
And just use path integral.

00:20:39.600 --> 00:20:43.080 align:middle line:84%
So path integrals,
in my own opinion,

00:20:43.080 --> 00:20:48.790 align:middle line:84%
have lots of advantage over
this interaction picture.

00:20:48.790 --> 00:20:50.310 align:middle line:84%
So when you do
interaction picture,

00:20:50.310 --> 00:20:52.200 align:middle line:84%
you get the feeling,
somehow, you're

00:20:52.200 --> 00:20:54.720 align:middle line:90%
doing some very clever tricks.

00:20:54.720 --> 00:20:58.050 align:middle line:84%
And you don't know why you
want to do those tricks.

00:20:58.050 --> 00:21:01.948 align:middle line:90%
And you get some nice formulas.

00:21:01.948 --> 00:21:03.990 align:middle line:84%
But somehow, you feel
you're doing a little bit--

00:21:03.990 --> 00:21:06.870 align:middle line:90%


00:21:06.870 --> 00:21:09.300 align:middle line:84%
yeah, you're doing
some kind of magic.

00:21:09.300 --> 00:21:12.780 align:middle line:84%
But the path
integral treatment is

00:21:12.780 --> 00:21:15.030 align:middle line:84%
automatic in the sense
it's straightforward.

00:21:15.030 --> 00:21:16.680 align:middle line:90%
And you don't have to think.

00:21:16.680 --> 00:21:19.020 align:middle line:84%
And it just follows
from the path integral.

00:21:19.020 --> 00:21:21.270 align:middle line:84%
And it's much easier
to generalize.

00:21:21.270 --> 00:21:23.160 align:middle line:90%
And it's physically intuitive.

00:21:23.160 --> 00:21:32.830 align:middle line:84%
And so that's why we will
describe this approach.

00:21:32.830 --> 00:21:35.350 align:middle line:84%
Because it's more
physically intuitive.

00:21:35.350 --> 00:21:37.870 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes, when you do too
much fancy mathematics,

00:21:37.870 --> 00:21:41.320 align:middle line:84%
you feel you obscure
the physical picture.

00:21:41.320 --> 00:21:44.672 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, this
interaction picture

00:21:44.672 --> 00:21:46.630 align:middle line:84%
gives you a little bit
of that kind of feeling.

00:21:46.630 --> 00:21:50.620 align:middle line:90%


00:21:50.620 --> 00:21:52.810 align:middle line:84%
But it's important
for you to know it.

00:21:52.810 --> 00:21:54.700 align:middle line:84%
We don't have time
to cover both.

00:21:54.700 --> 00:21:58.720 align:middle line:84%
And so we choose just
to do this in class.

