00:22:50.570 --> 00:23:06.620 align:middle line:90%


00:23:06.620 --> 00:23:09.860 align:middle line:84%
So path integral is
an alternative way

00:23:09.860 --> 00:23:12.350 align:middle line:90%
to formulate quantum mechanics.

00:23:12.350 --> 00:23:15.770 align:middle line:84%
It's equivalent, say, to
the Schrodinger equation

00:23:15.770 --> 00:23:17.370 align:middle line:90%
or Heisenberg equation.

00:23:17.370 --> 00:23:19.370 align:middle line:84%
It's equivalent to your
standard way of thinking

00:23:19.370 --> 00:23:21.980 align:middle line:90%
about quantum mechanics.

00:23:21.980 --> 00:23:25.880 align:middle line:84%
So path integral will give
you a better conceptual way

00:23:25.880 --> 00:23:29.510 align:middle line:84%
for non-relativistic
quantum mechanics.

00:23:29.510 --> 00:23:32.930 align:middle line:84%
Path integral, most
of the time, they

00:23:32.930 --> 00:23:38.880 align:middle line:84%
give you a better
conceptual way to think

00:23:38.880 --> 00:23:40.900 align:middle line:90%
about quantum mechanics.

00:23:40.900 --> 00:23:44.860 align:middle line:84%
But, in terms of
calculations, it often

00:23:44.860 --> 00:23:47.200 align:middle line:90%
does not offer any advantage.

00:23:47.200 --> 00:23:52.180 align:middle line:84%
So that's why the textbooks,
for undergraduate quantum

00:23:52.180 --> 00:23:55.372 align:middle line:84%
mechanics, they don't
just do path integral.

00:23:55.372 --> 00:23:57.580 align:middle line:84%
Because to do the calculation,
it's still much easier

00:23:57.580 --> 00:23:58.830 align:middle line:90%
to solve Schrodinger equation.

00:23:58.830 --> 00:24:02.530 align:middle line:90%


00:24:02.530 --> 00:24:06.342 align:middle line:84%
But conceptually, it gives
you a better picture.

00:24:06.342 --> 00:24:08.050 align:middle line:84%
And for quantum field
theory, it actually

00:24:08.050 --> 00:24:09.115 align:middle line:90%
become much more useful.

00:24:09.115 --> 00:24:13.103 align:middle line:90%


00:24:13.103 --> 00:24:14.395 align:middle line:90%
Is there any questions on this?

00:24:14.395 --> 00:24:17.640 align:middle line:90%


00:24:17.640 --> 00:24:18.140 align:middle line:90%
OK, good.

00:24:18.140 --> 00:24:18.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:24:18.640 --> 00:24:22.690 align:middle line:90%


00:24:22.690 --> 00:24:26.970 align:middle line:84%
OK, so first, we are
going just to review

00:24:26.970 --> 00:24:28.720 align:middle line:84%
the story for the
non-relativistic quantum

00:24:28.720 --> 00:24:31.900 align:middle line:90%
mechanics.

00:24:31.900 --> 00:24:35.950 align:middle line:84%
And once we understand this and
the immediate generalization--

00:24:35.950 --> 00:24:37.910 align:middle line:90%
the field theory is immediate.

00:24:37.910 --> 00:24:40.450 align:middle line:84%
Generalization to field
theory is immediate.

00:24:40.450 --> 00:24:48.640 align:middle line:84%
So we will just use the example
of just one particle, just

00:24:48.640 --> 00:24:51.100 align:middle line:84%
a particle in one
dimension, just

00:24:51.100 --> 00:24:54.250 align:middle line:90%
with the most familiar one.

00:24:54.250 --> 00:24:57.340 align:middle line:90%
So use this as an example.

00:24:57.340 --> 00:25:01.030 align:middle line:84%
Once we understand this
example, then you essentially

00:25:01.030 --> 00:25:02.495 align:middle line:90%
understand everything.

00:25:02.495 --> 00:25:07.310 align:middle line:90%


00:25:07.310 --> 00:25:09.350 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:25:09.350 --> 00:25:12.530 align:middle line:84%
So now the key point
about the path integral--

00:25:12.530 --> 00:25:16.070 align:middle line:90%


00:25:16.070 --> 00:25:18.030 align:middle line:84%
previously, in
quantum mechanics,

00:25:18.030 --> 00:25:21.530 align:middle line:84%
you start with the
Schrodinger equation.

00:25:21.530 --> 00:25:24.020 align:middle line:84%
But the path integral starts
with a different object.

00:25:24.020 --> 00:25:27.630 align:middle line:90%


00:25:27.630 --> 00:25:29.420 align:middle line:84%
So the object which
the path integral

00:25:29.420 --> 00:25:32.180 align:middle line:84%
is most convenient to
treat is the propagator

00:25:32.180 --> 00:25:33.035 align:middle line:90%
we discussed before.

00:25:33.035 --> 00:25:38.580 align:middle line:90%


00:25:38.580 --> 00:25:45.440 align:middle line:84%
So this is the object which
we defined, in the Heisenberg

00:25:45.440 --> 00:25:49.050 align:middle line:90%
picture, to be this object.

00:25:49.050 --> 00:25:50.930 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
transition amplitude.

00:25:50.930 --> 00:25:53.040 align:middle line:90%
If you have a particle--

00:25:53.040 --> 00:25:56.960 align:middle line:84%
if you have an eigenstate,
with x prime and t prime

00:25:56.960 --> 00:26:01.730 align:middle line:84%
and go into a position
eigenstate at the location, x,

00:26:01.730 --> 00:26:03.440 align:middle line:90%
at time t.

00:26:03.440 --> 00:26:06.803 align:middle line:84%
So we mentioned before,
if you load this object,

00:26:06.803 --> 00:26:07.970 align:middle line:90%
essentially it's equivalent.

00:26:07.970 --> 00:26:09.890 align:middle line:84%
You have solved the
Schrodinger equation.

00:26:09.890 --> 00:26:12.680 align:middle line:84%
Because from the wave
equation at t prime,

00:26:12.680 --> 00:26:17.420 align:middle line:90%
then by integrated with this--

00:26:17.420 --> 00:26:20.720 align:middle line:84%
convoluted with
this object, then

00:26:20.720 --> 00:26:22.420 align:middle line:84%
you can get the wave
function at time t.

00:26:22.420 --> 00:26:24.980 align:middle line:90%


00:26:24.980 --> 00:26:31.280 align:middle line:84%
And so this can also be written
in terms of Schrodinger picture

00:26:31.280 --> 00:26:36.530 align:middle line:90%
as this.

00:26:36.530 --> 00:26:40.550 align:middle line:84%
Just start with the
position eigenstate

00:26:40.550 --> 00:26:44.300 align:middle line:84%
at x prime, then you
evolve for t minus t prime,

00:26:44.300 --> 00:26:49.685 align:middle line:84%
and then you ask the
overlap with the x.

00:26:49.685 --> 00:26:53.796 align:middle line:90%


00:26:53.796 --> 00:26:56.410 align:middle line:90%
Any questions on this?

00:26:56.410 --> 00:27:00.460 align:middle line:90%
So let me call this object k.

00:27:00.460 --> 00:27:06.490 align:middle line:84%
This is k x t, x
prime, t prime, OK?

00:27:06.490 --> 00:27:10.730 align:middle line:84%
If you know the wave function,
so the wave function at t

00:27:10.730 --> 00:27:16.277 align:middle line:84%
x can be written as a wave
function at the t x prime, k t

00:27:16.277 --> 00:27:20.350 align:middle line:90%
x, t prime, x prime.

00:27:20.350 --> 00:27:24.060 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, I think I
